 due to LLM non-determinism. You need a real LLM call or a real ML classifier for relevance evaluation.","test_description":"Agentic test that calls a real LLM to generate a response to a specific customer question (e.g., 'How do I reset my password?'). Use a real relevance evaluator (semantic similarity, embedding-based matching, or LLM-as-judge) to verify the response addresses the question. Test multiple question-answer pairs and tone/tier variations to ensure the system doesn't produce off-topic content.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.75,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"The tone re-check correctly identifies when a response is too formal for a casual-tier customer and triggers regeneration.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"The tone-checking depends on a real classifier (LLM or ML model) that evaluates response formality. The real failure is 'the tone classifier didn't flag a formal response, so regeneration never triggered.' A Unit test mocking the tone classifier to return 'flagged=true' and verifying regeneration is triggered tests only the control flow, not the actual tone detection. A real tone classifier may categorize responses differently on different runs or across similar inputs. You need the real tone-checking model to verify this behavior.","test_description":"Agentic test using a real tone classifier or LLM to evaluate a formal response (e.g., 'Pursuant to the aforementioned account policy...') against a casual-tier customer's expected tone. Verify that the tone flag is raised and regeneration is requested. Test multiple formality levels and customer tiers to ensure the classifier correctly identifies tone mismatches. Verify that appropriate-tone responses do not trigger regeneration.","plan_consistent":true,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.1,"System":0.05,"Agentic":0.7,"Workflow":0.05}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"The full exchang